@page "/docs/springs"

<PageTitle>Springs — BlazorMotion</PageTitle>

<div class="breadcrumb">Docs / <span>Springs</span></div>
<h1>Springs</h1>
<p>Spring animations feel natural because they simulate real physics — velocity, stiffness, and damping. BlazorMotion runs the spring simulation in C# WASM each animation frame.</p>

<h2>Classic spring parameters</h2>
<pre><code>new TransitionConfig
{
    Type      = "spring",
    Stiffness = 200,   // How "stiff" the spring is (higher = snappier)
    Damping   = 20,    // Resistance (higher = less bounce)
    Mass      = 1,     // Virtual mass (higher = slower, more momentum)
    Velocity  = 0      // Initial velocity (px/s or units/s)
}</code></pre>

<h2>BounceSpring — visual API</h2>
<p>BlazorMotion also supports Framer Motion's intuitive bounce API:</p>
<pre><code>// Shorthand factory
TransitionConfig.BounceSpring(duration: 0.5, bounce: 0.25)

// Value range:
//   bounce = 0    → no bounce, critically damped
//   bounce = 0.25 → gentle bounce
//   bounce = 0.5  → moderate bounce
//   bounce = 1.0  → maximum bounce</code></pre>

<div class="demo-area" style="display:flex;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;justify-content:center;">
    @foreach (var (label, bounce) in new[] { ("No bounce", 0.0), ("Gentle", 0.25), ("Medium", 0.5), ("Bouncy!", 0.8) })
    {
        <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;">
            <Motion Class="demo-box"
                    Initial="@(new AnimationProps { Y = -60 })"
                    Animate="@(new AnimationProps { Y = 0 })"
                    Transition="@(TransitionConfig.BounceSpring(0.7, bounce))">
                @label
            </Motion>
            <span style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--text-muted)">bounce: @bounce</span>
        </div>
    }
</div>

